AVIAN INFLUENZA (50): JAPAN (KUMAMOTO) HPAI H5, POULTRY, OIE
************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Sun 13 Apr 2014
Source: OIE, WAHID (World Animal Health Information Database), weekly disease information 2014; 27(16) [edited]
http://www.oie.int/wahis_2/public/wahid.php/Reviewreport/Review?page_refer=MapFullEventReport&reportid=15109


Highly pathogenic avian influenza, Japan
----------------------------------------
Information received on [and dated] 13 Apr 2014 from Dr Toshiro Kawashima, CVO, Animal Health Division, Ministry of Agriculture, Forestry and Fisheries, Tokyo, Japan

Summary
Report type: immediate notification
Date of start of the event: 11 Apr 2014
Date of pre-confirmation of the event: 13 Apr 2014
Report date: 13 Apr 2014
Reason for notification: reoccurrence of a listed disease
Date of previous occurrence: 25 Mar 2011
Manifestation of disease: clinical disease
Causal agent: Highly pathogenic avian influenza virus
Serotype: H5
Nature of diagnosis: clinical, laboratory (basic), laboratory (advanced), necropsy
This event pertains to the whole country

New outbreaks (1)
Summary of outbreaks:
Total outbreaks: 1
Outbreak 1: Kuma-gun, Taragi-machi, Kumamoto
Date of start of the outbreak: 11 Apr 2014
Outbreak status: continuing (or date resolved not provided)
Epidemiological unit: farm
Affected animals:
Species / Susceptible / Cases / Deaths / Destroyed / Slaughtered
Birds / 56 400 / 200 / 200 / 56 200 / 0 /
Affected population: poultry (broiler)
Outbreak statistics (rates apparent, expressed in percentages):
Species / morbidity rate / mortality rate / case fatality rate / Proportion susceptible animals lost*
Birds / 0.35 / 0.35 / 100 / 19.45
*Removed from the susceptible population through death, destruction, and / or slaughter

Epidemiology
Source of the outbreak(s) or origin of infection: unknown or inconclusive
Epidemiological comments: infection with H5 influenza A virus in poultry was confirmed on 13 Apr 2014 in Kumamoto prefecture. On 12 Apr 2014, local veterinary officers visited the farm immediately after notification from the owner. Increase of the mortality was recognized and the local veterinary service centre in the prefecture (Kumamoto Livestock Hygiene Centre) confirmed that samples from dead birds were influenza A virus positive by antigen-capture kits. On the same day, the centre started RT-PCR test and confirmed that the subtype was H5 on [13 Apr 2014]. The samples are to be sent to the National Institute of Animal Health for virus isolation and HI test. Movement restrictions are imposed on the farms within the radius of 3 km [2 mi] of the affected farm. Shipment restrictions are imposed on the farms within the radius of 3-10 km [2-6 mi] of the affected farm. Stamping-out policy is applied to the affected farm and epidemiologically related farms. Destruction of all the susceptible birds in the affected farm and epidemiologically related farms will be completed on 13 Apr 2014.

Control measures
Measures applied: control of wildlife reservoirs; stamping out; quarantine; movement control inside the country; screening; disinfection of infected premises / establishment(s); vaccinated prohibited; no treatment of affected animals
Measures to be applied: no other measures

Diagnostic test results
Laboratory name and type / Species / Test / Test date / Result
Kumamoto Livestock Hygiene Centre (local laboratory) / Birds / reverse transcription-polymerase reaction (RT-PCR) / 13 Apr 2014 / Positive

Future reporting
The event is continuing. Weekly follow-up reports will be submitted.

[The location of the outbreak can be seen on the interactive map included in the OIE report at the source URL above.]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[According to Japan's media, citing officials on Tue 15 Apr 2014, the culling of 112 000 chickens, present on the affected farm and in a contact farm, has been completed while the authorities are stepping up efforts to "swiftly contain the outbreak".

The locations of HPAI H5 outbreaks in the region can be seen on the interactive OIE map at http://tinyurl.com/nq878rp (zoom in to the region). - Mod.AS/CRD

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=2405814,11009.]
